                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p38w38n7s/manifest/annotation/p2",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>as he stated for the above named society, called on me<lb/> and\n                                        after having taken the trouble twice to converse with<lb/>\n                                        him on religion, he felt so fully defeated, that\n                                        although<lb/> he promised to call again, he never did so. I\n                                        saw him<lb/> walking the streets frequently after that, and\n                                        I was told<lb/> by the minister of the fifth\n                                                  <sic>presbiterian</sic> church*, that he<lb/>\n                                        preached the <date>Sunday</date> following our arguments at\n                                        his<lb/> church, <sic>were</sic> he stated, that he visited\n                                        some of the jews<lb/> in this city, that he found them very\n                                        intelligent, and that<lb/> he entertained great hopes soon\n                                        to bring them to the<lb/> knowledge of divine truth. He has\n                                        not even been listened<lb/> to what his mission was, by any\n                                        other jew in this city, and<lb/> as to the truth of the\n                                        effects of my arguments, as above said<lb/> I will bring\n                                        christians who were present at the time to tes-<lb/>tify to\n                                        the same. This and similar facts with what I know<lb/> of\n                                                  <persName>Mr. M.</persName> up to this day, leads\n                                        me to suppose that those<lb/> Sharks after paying him what\n                                        they had agreed upon, to<lb/> compensate his soils in giving\n                                        them hebrew lessons, they ende-<lb/>vor to represent this as\n                                        a bribe to induce the above said<lb/> Gentl<hi rend=\"sup\"\n                                                  >n</hi> to change his religion. Now\n                                                  <sic>miself</sic> and many others<lb/> here will\n                                        prove that he regards money <hi rend=\"underline\">to</hi>\n                                        little ever to<lb/> fall a victim to such a snare. I have\n                                        ascertained<lb/> that he has instructed those men for nearly\n                                        four months<lb/> every day except <date>Saturday</date>\n                                        &amp; <date>Sunday</date>—for the small pittance<lb/> of 70\n                                        Dollars, and now it appears, since they full well knew<lb/>\n                                        that their stupid minds would not pick up sufficient<lb/>\n                                        hebrew an <sic>equevalence</sic> for their so much spoken of\n                                                  <add>?</add>,<lb/> they had a more jesuitic aim in\n                                        view in regard to <persName>Mr M.</persName><lb/> but since\n                                        they did not succeed, they try to revenge</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p38w38n7s/canvas/p2"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
