              "items": [
                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p38w38n7s/manifest/annotation/p3",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>themselves, by proclaiming to the world the flattering<lb/> hope of\n                                        the conversion of a Rabby.</p>\n                              <p>The position of these men, and especially that of <persName>Mr\n                                                  Bonahan</persName><lb/> is actually very\n                                        deplorable. The latter gentln although I have<lb/> no\n                                        personal knowledge of, I still have received such<lb/> a\n                                        description of his character by a very eminent\n                                        christian<lb/> a Gentl<hi rend=\"sup\">n</hi> of great\n                                        learning and thorough knowledge<lb/> to\n                                                  <sic>guarrantee</sic> my supposition, that we may\n                                        rely as much<lb/> on his assertions, as on those of any\n                                        other <add>מלמד</add>.</p>\n                              <p>What most surprised me was that, <persName>Mr. M.</persName>\n                                        condescended<lb/> even to take the least notice of the\n                                        slanderous productions<lb/> of a parcel of man, who for\n                                        money collected or almost-<lb/>extorted, from the blind\n                                        industrious portion of the community,<lb/> pretend to\n                                        undertake, to ameliorate the condition of a nation,<lb/> who\n                                        because being least, had ever to submit to all sorts<lb/> of\n                                        persecutions; at the same time losing <sic>intirely</sic>\n                                        sight<lb/> of the great defects existing among their own\n                                        people.<lb/> Considering them <sic>cristians</sic>, because\n                                        they curse &amp; swear by<lb/> the name of <sic>Crist</sic>.\n                                                  <hi rend=\"underline\">Who needs\n                                        conversion?</hi><lb/> Surely no man of sense! <hi\n                                                  rend=\"underline\">Besides can pecuniary<lb/>\n                                                  inducements convert a man</hi>? She will say\n                                        no!<lb/> Then why did these men of\n                                                  <placeName>Montgomery</placeName>\n                                        <sic>promiz</sic> him such<lb/> a glorious future of\n                                        indolence and opulence, if he would<lb/> only to consent to\n                                        stay with them, by which means they<lb/> supposed to produce\n                                        a rupture between him and his<lb/> people? Why bring those\n                                        by <persName>Mr. M.</persName> so hard earned paltry<lb/> 70\n                                        Dollars so emphatically into consideration. For my part<lb/>\n                                        I am so well <sic>aquainted</sic> with these petty\n                                                  <sic>manoevers</sic> such<lb/> as invitations to\n                                        prayer meetings, and other apparent brotherly</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p38w38n7s/canvas/p3"
                }
              ]
